Here’s how this repo is wired on GCP and what a **401** usually means.

## The API is reachable but not anonymous

Cloud Run can expose the service publicly, but **`apps/api` still requires auth** on almost everything. Only **`/health`** skips JWT verification; everything else goes through the `onRequest` hook:

```2041:2058:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\api\src\app.ts
    if (path === HEALTH_PATH) {
      return;
    }

    if (shouldSkipAuthForDevMediaSink(request.method, path)) {
      return;
    }

    const bearerToken = parseBearerToken(request.headers.authorization);
    if (!bearerToken) {
      throw new HttpError(401, "UNAUTHORIZED", "Bearer token is required.");
    }

    try {
      request.auth = await jwtVerifier(bearerToken);
    } catch {
      throw new HttpError(401, "UNAUTHORIZED", "Bearer token is invalid.");
    }
```

So the API is **not** “open” in the sense of unauthenticated access: the app must send **`Authorization: Bearer &lt;JWT&gt;`**, and the token must verify against **`JWT_ISSUER`**, **`JWT_AUDIENCE`**, and **`JWT_JWKS_URI`**.

## Two different 401 shapes

| Response / situation | Meaning |
|----------------------|--------|
| **Bearer token is required** | No `Authorization` header (or not a Bearer token). Often: user not signed in, or Firebase not configured in the built web app so no ID token is attached. |
| **Bearer token is invalid** | Header present but **`jwtVerify` failed** — wrong issuer/audience, expired token, wrong JWKS, etc. |

## Production Firebase + GCP (what must match)

For Firebase Hosting + Firebase Auth, **`docs/infrastructure.md`** specifies Secret Manager / Cloud Run env:

- **`JWT_ISSUER`** = `https://securetoken.google.com/<firebase_project_id>`
- **`JWT_AUDIENCE`** = **`<firebase_project_id>`** (same as Firebase/GCP project id)
- **`JWT_JWKS_URI`** = `https://www.googleapis.com/service_accounts/v1/jwk/securetoken@system.gserviceaccount.com`

Local dev uses **`JWT_AUDIENCE=memories-api`** (see `apps/api/scripts/local-auth-dev.ts`). If production secrets still use **`memories-api`** while the browser sends a **Firebase ID token** (audience = project id), verification fails → **401 invalid**.

## How the web app attaches the token

When Firebase env vars are present, `initFirebaseClient()` registers a provider that calls **`user.getIdToken()`**:

```52:60:c:\Users\Ken Levy\OneDrive\Documents\Business\Ohana\Memories\apps\web\src\lib\firebase.ts
  firebaseApp = initializeApp(config);
  registerFirebaseIdTokenProvider(async () => {
    const auth = getAuth(firebaseApp!);
    const user = auth.currentUser;
    if (!user) {
      return null;
    }
    return user.getIdToken();
  });
```

The API client prefers that token over the dev/localStorage token (`resolveBearerToken` in `apps/web/src/lib/api.ts`). So in production you need:

1. **`VITE_FIREBASE_*`** set correctly in the **Firebase Hosting** build (CI secrets per `docs/infrastructure.md`).
2. User **signed in** with Google (otherwise `getIdToken()` never runs → **token required**).
3. API **`JWT_*`** aligned with Firebase as above (**especially `JWT_AUDIENCE`**).

## Quick checks

1. **`curl https://&lt;your-api&gt;/health`** — should be **200** without auth (confirms the service is up).
2. Compare Cloud Run secret values to **section 3.1** in [`docs/infrastructure.md`](https://github.com/...) (Firebase issuer/audience/JWKS).
3. In the browser Network tab, inspect a failing API call: is **`Authorization: Bearer ...`** present? If missing → Firebase/sign-in/build config. If present → almost certainly **issuer/audience/JWKS** (or expired token).

**Bottom line:** On GCP the API is meant to be **publicly callable but JWT-protected**. A **401** is expected without a valid Bearer token or with JWT env vars that don’t match Firebase; it does **not** by itself mean Cloud Run or IAM is misconfigured for “opening” the service.

